{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "We use perplexity to assess the contribution of individual tokens in a statement to the overall commonsense contradiction.",
    "Given an input statement S = [w 1, w 2,..., w n], perplexity [24] measures how \"confused\" a language model is when predicting the entire sequence of words in S. A lower perplexity indicates that the model is more confident in its predictions, while a higher perplexity suggests less confidence in its predictions.",
    "In our framework, a transformer-based PLM is employed to identify nonsensical concepts within a statement by calculating its perplexity.",
    "Perplexity can be a useful indicator for detecting nonsensical concepts because it quantifies the likelihood of a given sequence of words according to the model's learned knowledge.",
    "Specifically, given a sentence like \"My dad grew volleyballs in his garden,\" the model assigns a high perplexity score due to the implausibility of the event described."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Given an input statement S = [w 1, w 2,..., w n], perplexity [24] measures how \"confused\" a language model is when predicting the entire sequence of words in S. A lower perplexity indicates that the model is more confident in its predictions, while a higher perplexity suggests less confidence in its predictions."
  ]
}